{
  "query": "How does the success of providing artificial nest sites for solitary bees compare to providing them for bumblebees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on evidence from multiple replicated trials, artificial nest sites for solitary bees show significantly higher success rates and occupancy compared to bumblebee nest boxes. For solitary bees, 29 out of 30 replicated trials across 10 countries showed occupancy, with many species readily using nest boxes including some endangered species. Studies report occupancy rates between 1-26% of available cavities, with some trials showing the number of occupied nests doubling over three years with repeated provision. In contrast, bumblebee nest boxes show much lower uptake rates, with three UK trials since 1989 showing very low uptake of 0-2.5%, though some earlier studies (pre-1978) reported 10-48% occupancy. Underground nest boxes for bumblebees appear most effective with 6-58% occupancy in seven trials, but overall, wooden surface nest boxes commonly marketed for wildlife gardening show poor performance with 0-1.5% occupancy in recent UK studies.",
