{
  "query": "What is the evidence regarding the timeframe for bee colonization of newly created nesting habitats?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence shows that newly created nesting habitats can be colonized by bees within relatively short timeframes. For ground-nesting bee habitats, artificially exposed areas of bare soil can be successfully colonized by ground-nesting solitary bees and wasps in the first or second year after creation (Action ID: 13). For artificial nest sites, multiple replicated trials demonstrate that solitary bees readily occupy nest boxes, with studies across Europe, North and South America, and Asia showing occupancy rates. One replicated trial in Germany showed that the number of occupied solitary bee nests can double over three years with repeated nest box provision at a given site (Action ID: 47). Another replicated trial in Germany demonstrated that the number of occupied solitary bee nests almost doubled over three years with repeated nest box provision (Action ID: 80). These findings indicate that bees can colonize new nesting habitats quickly, within one to two years for ground habitats, with population increases observable over three-year periods for artificial nest boxes.",
