{"summary": "Based on the documented evidence, reducing farming intensity can have mixed effects on wild bee populations. For tillage reduction, evidence is mixed with two replicated trials on squash farms in the USA showing contrasting results - one found no difference in bee abundance between tilled and untilled farms, while another found three times more squash bees (Peponapis pruinosa) on no-till farms compared to conventional farms (action IDs 11, 789).

For meadow management intensity, four replicated trials in Europe compared extensively managed meadows with conventionally farmed meadows or silage fields. Two studies found enhanced numbers and diversity of wild bees on meadows with delayed first cutting and little agrochemical use, while two studies found no difference in bee diversity or abundance between conventional meadows and those with reduced fertilizer use or cutting intensity (action ID 22).

Regarding grazing intensity, one replicated trial showed that reducing summer cattle grazing intensity can increase the abundance (but not species richness) of cavity-nesting bees and wasps (action ID 23). Studies on delayed cutting or grazing dates on grasslands showed variable responses for butterflies and moths, with some finding greater abundance when cutting was delayed until July or September compared to May or June cutting, though results were not consistent across all years (action ID 3967). One study on increased grazing intensity found lower abundance of adult butterflies at intensively grazed sites compared to lightly or ungrazed sites (action ID 3962).", "action_ids": ["11", "789", "22", "23", "3967", "3962"], "query": "What are the documented effects of reducing the intensity of farming practices, such as tillage, grazing, and meadow management, on wild bee populations?"}

