  "query": "What actions, other than providing bare ground, can be taken to create or enhance nesting sites for various bee species?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several actions can be taken to create or enhance nesting sites for various bee species besides providing bare ground: Provide artificial nest sites for solitary bees using cut hollow stems or tubes (23 replicated trials showed occupation) and blocks of wood drilled with holes (11 trials demonstrated occupation). Reed stem and wooden grooved-board nest boxes were found to be most productive, while plastic-lined holes, plastic or paper tubes were less productive due to parasitism or mould. Nest boxes should be placed 150-600 m from forage resources, as estimated by replicated experiments in Germany. Cardboard straws placed in drilled wooden holes were found more productive for the oil-collecting bee Centris analis in Brazil than grooved wooden boards stacked together. Repeated provision of nest boxes at sites can lead to doubling of occupied solitary bee nests over three years, as shown in trials from agricultural land in India, Germany and the USA. However, nest boxes can also be subject to parasite and predator attacks, with mortality rates ranging from 2% to 56%. Introduced species may also occupy nest boxes more commonly than native bees in some areas.",
